Direct Known Subclasses:
EnvelopeHorizon
public class Envelope
extends Rectangle2D.Double
implements Polygon, Serializable

This class implements a 2D rectangular shape in world coordinates, used frequently for bitmap and selection purposes. This is implemented as a class rather than an interface because it is used very frequently, so fast access to member variables is more desirable than the flexibility of an interface.

See Also:
ClementiniGeometry, Serialized Form

getEnvelopeByRef

public Envelope getEnvelopeByRef()
Description copied from interface: Geometry
Determines the bounding box of the geometry. This method returns a reference to an existing envelope.

This method is provided to reduce memory consumption and should be used with care. Modifications should not be made to the returned envelope. Implementing classes are free to return an actual reference or a completely new object providing it is stated in the method's documentation.

Specified by:

the envelope bounding box

clipLine

public boolean clipLine(double x1,
                        double y1,
                        double x2,
                        double y2,
                        int code1,
                        Point pt)
Uses the Cohen-Sutherland clipping algorithm to determine where the envelope will clip the line. The code1 argument is used to determine which edge of the envelope will be used to clip the line. The following list contains the valid bit codes and their appropriate meanings:
  • 9 - top left corner
  • 8 - top
  • 10 - top right corner
  • 1 - left side
  • 2 - right side
  • 5 - bottom left corner
  • 4 - bottom
  • 6 - bottom right corner

Parameters:
x1 - the X ordinate of the line's starting point
y1 - the Y ordinate of the line's starting point
x2 - the X ordinate of the line's ending point
y2 - the Y ordinate of the line's ending point
code1 - clipping edge bit flag
pt - the resulting clip point if successful
Returns:
true, if the line was successfully clipped, false otherwise

grow

public void grow(double f)
Zooms the current Envelope using the given scale factor. The Envelope zooming is centred on the Envelope centre. A scale factor > 1 causes the Envelope to become larger while, a factor < 1 causes it to become smaller.

buffer

public Polygon buffer(double bufferDistance,
                      double minOrdDistance)
Description copied from interface: FeatureGeometry
This method generates the outer shell of a feature geometry. No donut holes are created. It assumes that the feature is valid, that means the order of the points is in CCW mode for polygons, and that there are no repeated or duplicate points.

Specified by:
buffer in interface FeatureGeometry
Parameters:
bufferDistance - the buffer distance
minOrdDistance - the maximum deviation allowed from the generated chords to the conceptual circular curve. the mid-ordinant distance is the maximum distance from a chord with its endpoints on the curve to the curve itself.
Returns:
the buffer polygon
See Also:
InvalidDistanceException

calcIntersection

public Envelope calcIntersection(Envelope e)
Calculates the intersection between this Envelope and the user specified one. If are four possible outcomes of this calculation: no intersection, point, line, and envelope. If the envelopes do not intersect, the height and width will be negative. If the intersection is a point, both the height and width will be zero. If the intersection is a line, either the height or the width will be zero (but not both).

Parameters:
e - input envelope
Returns:
envelope of resulting intersection

Determines if the current envelope has zero width and height.

Returns:
True if Envelope is a point, else False

isLine

public boolean isLine()
Determines if the current Envelope has zero width or zero height, but not both.

Returns:
True for zero height or zero width, else False

isNothing

public boolean isNothing()
Determines if the current Envelope does not have height or width.

Returns:
True if no height or no width, else False

isBox

public boolean isBox()
Determines if the current Envelope is rectangular in shaped.

Returns:
True if the envelope has a height and width, both greater than 0.0.
